So what exactly "Half-life" (1998) taught people?

1)Shooters with stories are actually awesome. At a time when half-life 1 came out, popular shooters were without any story. Consider, for example, Quake 2 (1997) that was based entirely on combat (no story, no dialog), you just need to shoot - that's all. Such game process gets boring pretty quick because of it's repetetive process. Funny though, after so many years even modern shooters make the same mistake and either have no story at all or just a small backstory;

2)Cut-scenes are bad. It's so better without them, because you sink more into the story and you actually enjoy it, the same cannot be said for cutscenes, which many players just skip;

3)AI enemies shouldn't just move straight to you. They need to take cover, shoot from save positions and run away if they need to do it;

4)Scribtable destruction of environment is fun.
